ris Doctor|JD]])<br>[[Princeton University]] ([[Master of Public Administration|MPA]])\n|website         = {{url|lance.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Leonard J. Lance''' (born June 25, 1952) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NJ|7}}, serving since 2009. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He previously served in the [[New Jersey Senate]] and the [[New Jersey General Assembly]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nLance was born in [[Easton, Pennsylvania]], into a political family. His parents were Anne M. (n\u00e9e Anderson) and [[Wesley Lance|Wesley Leonard Lance]], who was a State Senator.<ref>[http://region.princeton.edu/about_advisory_bio_54.html Hon. Leonard Lance (MPA '82)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210110150/http://region.princeton.edu/about_advisory_bio_54.html |date=February 10, 2007 }}, [[Princeton University]] Policy Research Institute for the Region. Accessed May 11, 2007.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/lance.htm|title=leonard lance|publisher=}}</ref> His great-uncle, H. Kiefer Lance, was also active in New Jersey politics.\n\nAfter attending [[North Hunterdon High School]] in [[Annandale, New Jersey]], Lance received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Lehigh University]] in 1974, a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Vanderbilt University Law School]] in 1977 and an [[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]] from the [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]] at [[Princeton University]] in New Jersey in 1982.<ref name=NJLEG>[http://www.njleg.state.nj.us/members/BIO.asp?Leg=71 Senator Lance's legislative web page], [[New Jersey Legislature]]. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nLeonard Lance served as the law clerk to the [[Warren County, New Jersey|Warren County]] Court in 1977 and 1978. He was assistant counsel for county and municipal matters to [[Governor of New Jersey]] [[Thomas Kean]] from 1983 to 1990. He was a member of the New Jersey Council on the Humanities during the [[Christine Todd Whitman|Whitman]] Administration by appointment of the Governor.\n\n==New Jersey legislature==\nLance served in the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] for 11 years (1991\u20132002) and served in the [[New Jersey Senate]] for 7 years (2002\u20132009). In 2002 he was elected to the [[New Jersey Senate]] and held the position of [[Minority Leader]] from 2004 to 2008.<ref name=NJLEG/> While serving in the state legislature, he gained a reputation as a moderate Republican.<ref name=twsSLedger898>Tom Moran, May 22, 2011, ''The Star-Ledger'', [http://blog.nj.com/njv_tom_moran/2011/05/the_curious_transformation_of.html The curious transformation of N.J. Congressman Leonard Lance], Retrieved January 29, 2017, \"......\"</ref>\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1987, he first ran for the General Assembly. He lost the Republican primary, ranking third with 17% in New Jersey's 23rd District.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=723038 |title=NJ General Assembly 23 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 02, 1987 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> Lance was appointed to the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] in February 1991 when then-Assemblyman [[William E. Schluter]] was appointed to the [[New Jersey Senate]] upon the ascension of [[Dick Zimmer (New Jersey politician)|Dick Zimmer]] from the [[New Jersey Senate]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]] in January 1991.  After redistricting, Lance ran for the newly redrawn 23rd District in 1991, and won the Republican primary. In the general election, he ranked second with 30%, winning a seat. Incumbent Republican State Assemblyman [[Chuck Haytaian]] ranked first in the district with 33%.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=241047 |title=NJ General Assembly 23 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1991 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> In 1993, Lance won re-election to a second term with 40%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=149409 |title=NJ General Assembly 23 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 1993 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> In 1995, he won re-election to a third term with 34%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=218787 |title=NJ General Assembly 23 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 1995 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> In 1997, he won re-election to a fourth term with 30%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=719396 |title=NJ General Assembly 23 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1997 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> In 1999, he won re-election to a fifth term with 36%.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=36972 |title=NJ General Assembly 23 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1999 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter redistricting, he ran for the [[New Jersey Senate]] in 2001 in the 23rd District. He defeated Democrat Frederick P. Cook 69%\u201331%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=3603 |title=NJ State Senate 23 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2001 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> In 2003, he won re-election to a second term with 68%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=20012 |title=NJ State Senate 23 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2003 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> In 2007, he won re-election to a third term with 67%.<ref name=\"ourcampaigns.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=338935 |title=NJ State Senate 23 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2007 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n\n===Elections===\n;1996\nIn 1996, Leonard Lance sought the Republican nomination to replace Rep. [[Dick Zimmer (New Jersey politician)|Dick Zimmer]], who was retiring from the House of Representatives to run for the United States Senate.  Lance ran to represent [[New Jersey's 12th congressional district|New Jersey\u2019s 12th congressional district]], which at that time included his residence in Clinton Township.  Lance finished third in the primary behind [[Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey|Franklin Township]] Mayor [[Michael Pappas]] and New Jersey Senator [[John O. Bennett III]].  Pappas went on to win the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=46016 |title=NJ District 12 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 04, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2008#District 7}}\nIn 2008, Lance ran for Congress in the 7th congressional district, which now included his residence in Clinton Township.  Republican Rep. [[Mike Ferguson (New Jersey politician)|Mike Ferguson]] was retiring after four terms in Congress.  In the Republican primary, Lance faced seven candidates including former [[Summit, New Jersey|Summit]] Council President Kelly Hatfield, Scotch Plains Mayor Martin Marks and Kate Whitman, daughter of former New Jersey Governor [[Christine Todd Whitman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/south/index.ssf/2008/05/some_things_readers_should_kno.html |title=Some things readers should know about NJ's June 3 primary election |website=[[The Star-Ledger]] |date= May 17, 2008 |accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref> On June 3, 2008, Lance won the Republican primary with 40% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njelections.org/election-results/2008-official-pri-elect-house-candidate-tallies-071108.pdf |title= Official List: Candidate Returns for House of Representatives For June 2008 Primary Election |publisher=njelections.org|accessdate= February 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Lance faced New Jersey Assemblywoman [[Linda Stender]] of [[Scotch Plains, New Jersey|Scotch Plains]] as well as three independent and third party candidates.  Stender had run against Rep. Ferguson in 2006 and lost narrowly.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.westfieldleader.com/06nov09/06nov09.pdf |title=Incumbent Menendez Maintains Seat, Kean Loses Senate Race |publisher=Westfield Leader |date=November 6, 2005}}</ref> ''[[The Cook Political Report]]'' rated the race as a \"toss up.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160529123927/http://cookpolitical.com/archive/chart/house/race-ratings/2008-11-04_13-32-49 ]</ref> Lance was endorsed by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=For the House|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/25/opinion/25sat4.html|website=The New York Times}}</ref> On November 4, Lance defeated Stender by 51% to 41%. Lance was one of two Republicans elected for the first time in a district that President [[Barack Obama]] won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frontloading.blogspot.com/2009/03/2008-electoral-college-by-congressional.html |title=Frontloading HQ: 2008 Electoral College by Congressional District |publisher=Frontloading.blogspot.com |date=2009-03-10 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 presidential primaries, Lance supported Massachusetts Governor [[Mitt Romney]]. He later endorsed [[John McCain]].<ref>[http://www.nj.com/reporter/index.ssf/2008/10/local_republicans_to_hold_john.html Local Republicans to hold John McCain, Sarah Palin 'All-American Rally' in Somerville], Retrieved March 12, 2017</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2010#District 7}}\n\nIn 2010, Lance was challenged in the Republican primary by businessman David Larsen of Oldwick, IT consultant Alonzo Hosford of Milford, and real estate appraiser Bruce Baker of Westfield.  Lance won the primary with 56% of the vote, ahead of Larsen with 31%, Hosford with 8% and Baker with 5%.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Mills/The Star-Ledger |url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2010/06/us_rep_lance_clinches_republic.html |title=U.S. Rep. Leonard Lance clinches Republican nomination in the 7th District |publisher=NJ.com |date=2010-06-08 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=643628 |title=NJ District 7 - R Primary Race - Jun 08, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref> Unlike the 2008 election, the 2010 7th district general election race was not considered competitive.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160529123806/http://cookpolitical.com/archive/chart/house/race-ratings/2010-11-01_12-12-36 ]</ref> Lance defeated educator Ed Potosnak 59% to 41%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=496869 |title=NJ - District 07 Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2012#District 7}}\n\nRedistricting made Lance's district significantly more Republican than its predecessor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1211/70817.html |title=New Jersey remap a lump of coal for Democrats |first=Alex |last=Isenstadt |publisher=Politico |date=December 23, 2011 |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Amick |first=George |url=http://www.nj.com/mercer/index.ssf/2012/01/the_effects_of_congressional_r.html |title=The effects of congressional redistricting in Mercer |publisher=NJ.com |date= |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> The 7th was pushed to the north, shedding several Democratic-leaning portions of Middlesex County in exchange for more conservative territory in Morris and Warren Counties. It also absorbed all of Hunterdon County.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shafer |first=Jack |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2011/12/nj-remap-a-setback-for-democrats-070817 |title=N.J. remap a setback for Democrats |publisher=Politico |date=2011-12-23 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref> In the Republican congressional primary, Lance was challenged for a second time by David Larsen. Lance defeated Larsen 61% to 39%.<ref>{{cite web|author=File Photo |url=http://www.nj.com/hunterdon-county-democrat/index.ssf/2012/06/lance_defeats_larsen_in_7th_di.html |title=Lance defeats Larsen in 7th District Republican primary for Congress |publisher=NJ.com |date=2012-06-05 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref> In the general election, Lance defeated New Jersey Assemblyman [[Upendra Chivukula]] 57% to 40%.<ref>http://www.politico.com/2012-election/results/house/new-jersey/</ref>\n\nIn the Republican presidential primaries, Lance endorsed Mitt Romney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.app.com/capitolquickies/2011/10/26/u-s-rep-leonard-lance-endorses-romney/ |title=U.S. Rep. Leonard Lance endorses Romney &#124; Capitol QuickiesCapitol Quickies |publisher=Blogs.app.com |date=2011-10-26 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2014#District 7}}\n\nLance was challenged for a third time for the Republican nomination by David Larsen.  Lance defeated Larsen 54% to 46%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/2014/results/primaries/new-jersey |title=New Jersey Primary Results - Election 2014 |publisher=NYTimes.com |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref> In the general election, Lance defeated [[Clinton, New Jersey|Town of Clinton]] Mayor Janice Kovachs 59% to 39%.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peters |first=Sarah |url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/elections/index.ssf/2014/11/district_7_race_leonard_lance.html |title=New Jersey District 7: Leonard Lance trumps Janice Kovach to secure fourth term |publisher=lehighvalleylive.com |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2016#District 7}}\n\nIn the 2016 Republican congressional primary, Lance was challenged by David Larsen for a fourth time.  Businessman Craig Heard of Roxbury also ran in the primary.  Lance won the primary with 54% of the vote, ahead of Larsen with 33% and Heard with 13%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2016/06/nj_primary_election_results_2016_us_congress.html |title=Live results: N.J. congressional primary election results 2016 |publisher=NJ.com |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Aun |first=Fred J. |url=https://www.tapinto.net/towns/roxbury/articles/roxburys-craig-heard-aims-to-oust-lance-in-gop-p |title=Roxbury's Craig Heard Aims to Oust Lance in GOP Primary Race - Roxbury NJ News |publisher=TAPinto |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref> In the general election, Lance faced social worker Peter Jacob. Jacob was one of 27 congressional candidates endorsed by presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Alyana Alfaro |url=http://observer.com/2016/08/new-bernie-sanders-org-endorses-cd7-challenger-jacob/ |title=New Bernie Sanders Organization Endorses NJ-7 Challenger Jacob |publisher=Observer |date=2016-08-25 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ourrevolution.com/election-2016/ |title=LiveTracker |publisher=Our Revolution |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref> Lance defeated Jacob 54% to 43%.<ref>{{cite web|last=New |first=The |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-jersey-house-district-7-lance-jacob |title=New Jersey U.S. House 7th District Results: Leonard Lance Wins \u2013 Election Results 2016 \u2013 The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2017-08-01 |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n;2018\n\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2018#District 7}}\n\nLance will face former [[Assistant Secretary of State for Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor]] [[Tom Malinowski]] in the November 2018 general election.\n\n===Tenure===\n\nLance was sworn in as a Member of Congress on January 6, 2009, and was appointed to the [[House Financial Services Committee]], where he worked on a wide range of issues relating to the financial services sector and the American economy. In 2011 Congressman Leonard Lance left the [[House Financial Services Committee]] and has been appointed to the House Energy and Commerce Committee.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hughes|first1=Karen|title=Congressman Leonard Lance Endorses Bourke and Mount for Re-Election to Millburn Township Committee|website=TapintoMilburn|publisher=Milburn Patch|accessdate=March 12, 2017|ref=https://www.tapinto.net/towns/millburn-slash-short-hills/articles/congressman-leonard-lance-endorses-bourke-and-mou}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lance was named to the [[House Ethics Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Herb|title=N.J.'s Lance tapped for ethics panel|url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2017/01/03/after-uproar-2-nj-say-they-opposed-ethics-rule-change/96108578/|website=NorthJersey.com|publisher=Gannett|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]] (Vice Chair)\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Digital Commerce and Consumer Protection|Subcommittee on Digital Commerce and Consumer Protection]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n\n;Caucus Memberships\n;*[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n;*Congressional Israel Allies Caucus\n;*House Republican Israel Caucus\n;*Rare Disease Caucus\n;*Congressional Pediatric and Adult Hydrocephalus Caucus\n\n;*Congressional Humanities Caucus\n;*Congressional Caucus on the Deadliest Cancers\n;*Congressional Problem Solvers Caucus\n;*[[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n;*'''[[Climate Solutions Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=| publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> \n\nLance also serves as the Republican chairman of the Rare Disease Caucus. The goal of the caucus is to get Members of Congress to support passing bills that help people who suffer from rare diseases.<ref name=nj201412raredisease>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hunterdon-county-democrat/index.ssf/2014/12/congressman_leonard_lance_will_1.html|title=Congressman Leonard Lance will continue as Republican Chair of Congressional Rare Disease Caucus|publisher=}}</ref> Seventy-six Members of Congress are caucus members.\n\nLance is also a member of the [[Problem Solvers Caucus]].  The goal of the caucus is to work in a bipartisan way to solve important issues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/12/17/571443669/rep-leonard-lance-on-gop-tax-bill|title=Rep. Leonard Lance On GOP Tax Bill|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Brett Kavanaugh 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Lance described Supreme Court nominee [[Brett Kavanaugh]] as a brilliant judge and he \"did not tend to believe the charges\" brought forth by [[Christine Blasey Ford]] regarding sexual assault.<ref name=twsNYT10143> Nate Schweber and Nick Corasaniti, September 28, 2018, \nThe New York Times, [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/28/nyregion/Vulnerable-new-jersey-republican-defends-kavanaugh-jolting-race.html Vulnerable New Jersey Republican Defends Kavanaugh, Jolting Race], Retrieved September 29, 2018, \"...Judge Kavanaugh is a brilliant judge and I tend not to believe the charges...\"</ref>]]\nAs of July 2018, Lance had voted with his party in 86.1% of votes so far in the [[115th United States Congress]] and voted in line with President Trump's position in 87.1% of votes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/leonard-lance/|title=Tracking Leonard Lance In The Age Of Trump|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=January 30, 2017|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=July 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=propublica>{{Cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/members/L000567-leonard-lance|title=Represent|last=|first=|work=ProPublica|access-date=July 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLance describes himself as a \"moderate conservative\" and a \"deficit hawk.\" In 2018, [[NJ.com]] described him as \"New Jersey's most vulnerable Republican lawmaker in a state that clearly doesn't like President Donald Trump,\" making him \"more willing to vote against Trump and his GOP colleagues.\" In 2017, his voting record was more liberal and less conservative than his lifetime record in Congress, causing Lance's ratings from conservative interest groups to dip while his ratings from liberal interest groups improved. He opposed efforts by his party to repeal the [[Affordable Care Act]] and voted against the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]], which targeted New Jersey and other high-tax states. ''[[Congressional Quarterly]]'' found that only eight other Republican members of Congress were more likely than Lance to cross party lines. In the first session of the [[115th United States Congress]], the [[Lugar Center]] rated Lance the 13th most bipartisan House member, up from 75th in 2016.<ref name=salant>{{cite news|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan|title=This N.J. Republican is in big trouble because of Trump. Here's what he's doing about it.|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/how_njs_most_endangered_congressman_is_trying_to_w.html|accessdate=22 May 2018|publisher=NJ.com|date=May 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/Senate%20Scores%20115th%20Congress%20First%20Session.pdf|publisher=The Lugar Center|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=April 24, 2018|accessdate=July 3, 2018|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n=== Budget and economy ===\nIn 2011 Lance voted for the [[Balanced budget amendment]] to the [[United States Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/new-jersey/woodbridge/lance-supports-a-balanced-budget-amendment-in-the-facbd913de310|title=Lance Supports a Balanced Budget Amendment in the Face of a $15 Trillion Deficit|website=patch.com|publisher=Woodbridge Patch|last1=Bell|first1=Deborah|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>  He also opposed President Obama\u2019s [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] and argued that it contained too much wasteful government spending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/jessica-coomes/index.ssf/2009/02/democratic_group_targets_leona.html|title=Democratic group targets Leonard Lance's vote against stimulus|website=LehighValleyLive|publisher=Lehigh Valley Live|last1=Coomes|first1=Jessica|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLance voted against the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]]. He was one of four Republicans from New Jersey to vote against the bill. He cited New Jersey's high property taxes and poor deductions for being the rationale behind his vote.<ref name=\"Mishkin122017\">{{cite web|last1=Mishkin|first1=Leah|title=In a major victory for the GOP, tax bill passes House and Senate {{!}} Video {{!}} NJTV News|url=https://www.njtvonline.org/news/video/major-victory-gop-tax-bill-passes-house-senate/|website=NJTV News|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> On poor deductions, he specifically pointed to the lack of state and local tax deductions (SALT) in the law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-jersey/story/2017/12/05/gottheimer-and-lance-make-last-ditch-effort-to-save-salt-deduction-133711|title=Gottheimer and Lance make last-ditch effort to save SALT deduction|work=Politico PRO|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\nAs of September 2018, [[FiveThirtyEight]] has found that Lance votes with President Trump 88% of the time, and is the 31st-most partisan Trump supporter in the House when compared to his district's voting patterns as of September 26, 2018.<ref name=\"Five38\">[https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/house/ Tracking Congress in the Age of Trump], accessed September 25, 2018</ref>\n\nIn the 2016 presidential primaries, Lance endorsed New Jersey Governor [[Chris Christie]]. He endorsed [[Donald Trump]] in the general election, saying that \"I have always supported the Republican nominee for President of the United States dating back to my first vote for Richard M. Nixon in 1972. While no one would confuse my personality with his, Donald Trump will have my enthusiastic support for President against Hillary Clinton or Bernie Sanders.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lance Endorses Trump for President|author=Max Pizarro|date=May 4, 2016|access-date=January 7, 2017|publisher=Observer|website=observer.com|url=http://observer.com/2016/05/lance-endorses-trump-for-president/}}</ref>\n\nAfter endorsing Donald Trump in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 election]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/leonard-lance/|title=Tracking Congress in the Age of Trump|author=Aaron Bycoffe|access-date=January 7, 2017|publisher=FiveThirtyEight}}</ref> Lance has criticized at least one of the President\u2019s early policies. Lance condemned President Trump's 2017 executive order that curtailed the immigration of people from seven countries in the Middle East, calling it \"rushed and poorly implemented.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2017/01/30/nj-delegation-reacts-trump-action-refugees-muslims/97255112/|title=NJ delegation reacts to Trump action on refugees, Muslims|website=northjersey.com|publisher=Gannett|last1=Herb|first1=Jackson|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> Lance was supportive of Trump's nomination of [[Neil Gorsuch]] to the United States Supreme Court<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tapinto.net/towns/springfield/articles/lance-statement-on-judge-gorsuchs-nomination-to|title=Lance Statement on Judge Gorsuch's Nomination to the U.S. Supreme Court|website=tapinto.net|publisher=Springfield Patch|last1=Dickson|first1=Ellen}}</ref> and his [[Mexico City Policy]].<ref name=\"WNYC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/the-takeaway-2017-01-31/|title=Immigration Ban: The Republican Response, the Christian Response, and the Complexities of Digital Security|website=The Takeaway|publisher=WNYC}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, protesters taking part in the [[2017 Women's March]] marched to Lance's office in [[Westfield, New Jersey]].<ref name=twsTAPinto4932>Jackie Lieberman, TAPinto, [https://www.tapinto.net/towns/westfield/articles/womens-march-in-westfield-attracts-thousands Women\u2019s March in Westfield Attracts Thousands], Retrieved January 26, 2017, \"... the crowd walked along North Avenue through Downtown Westfield to Congressman Leonard Lance\u2019s office at 425 North Ave. East&nbsp;...\"</ref><ref name=twsNJcom9920>Kelly Heyboer, January 18, 2017, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2017/01/6_sister_marches_in_nj_on_day_after_trump_inaugura.html Women's March to include 6 'sister marches' in N.J. on Saturday], Retrieved January 26, 2017, \"...&nbsp;Marchers are scheduled to gather in front of the Lord & Taylor on North Avenue in Westfield and march about a half mile to the office of Rep. Leonard Lance (R- 7th Dist.).&nbsp;...\"</ref> In Watchung in 2017, citizens groups opposed to the policies of [[Donald Trump]] vowed to hold representatives accountable, and specifically targeted Lance and senators [[Cory Booker]] and [[Robert Menendez]] accountable to the wishes of voters, not the president.<ref name=twsES494>Alex Parker-Magyar, ''Echoes Sentinel'', January 25, 2017, [http://www.newjerseyhills.com/echoes-sentinel/news/watchung-hills-residents-vow-to-hold-representatives-accountable-under-trump/article_de8fa0c1-3eba-54b8-a4d8-7e02e209a96c.html Watchung Hills residents 'VOW' to hold representatives accountable under Trump], Retrieved January 26, 2017, \"...&nbsp;citizens group, ... aims to hold politicians - namely Rep. Leonard Lance, R-7, ... accountable to the voters, not the wishes of the new president.&nbsp;...\"</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Lance rejected [[Roy Moore]], who was supported by Trump as the Republican candidate in the [[United States Senate special election in Alabama, 2017|U.S. Senate special election in Alabama]], telling [[Chris Cuomo]] of [[CNN]]'s ''[[New Day (TV series)|New Day]]'' that \"I do not think he should be elected to the United States Senate\" and urging voters in Alabama to write in an alternate Republican.<ref>Ellefson, Lindsey. [http://www.cnn.com/2017/11/22/politics/leonard-lance-roy-moore-new-day-cnntv/index.html \"GOP congressman won't support Roy Moore\"], ''[[CNN]]'', November 22, 2017. Accessed January 1, 2018. \"Republican representative Leonard Lance during a Wednesday morning appearance on CNN's ''New Day'' supported the women who have come forward with allegations against Alabama Senate candidate Roy Moore.... 'I believe the women and I do not think he should be elected to the United States Senate,' Lance told anchor Chris Cuomo.... He said he hoped 'the people of Alabama might write in a Republican,' which is what Shelby has stated he plans to do.\"</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nLance's lifetime score from the [[League of Conservation Voters]] is 23%; his 2017 score was 34%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/members-of-congress|title=National Environmental Scorecard|website=lcv.com|publisher=League of Conservation Voters|accessdate=February 28, 2018}}</ref> As of October 2018, his rating on [[Clean Water Action]]'s scorecard for the 115th congressional session was 33%.<ref>{{cite web |title=Representative Leonard Lance (NJ-07\u2013R) |url=https://cleanwaterscorecard.org/2018/09/06/representative-leonard-lance-nj-07-r/ |publisher=Clean Water Action |accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nLance supported the [[Keystone XL Pipeline]] but has opposed pipelines in New Jersey. In 2014, Lance voted for H.R. 5682, which authorized TransCanada Keystone Pipeline, L.P. to construct, connect, operate, and maintain the pipeline and cross-border facilities. He said \"The project will create American jobs and American energy and reduce North America's dependence on foreign oil. It has bipartisan support in Congress and the backing of labor and business alike.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lance.house.gov/newsroom/press-releases/lance-final-environmental-report-clears-path-for-keystone-xl|date=Jan 31, 2014|accessdate=Jan 2, 2017|title=Final Environmental Report Clears Path For Keystone XL|website=house.gov|publisher=US House of Representatives}}</ref> Lance opposed the [[PennEast Pipeline]], which crosses New Jersey, saying that \"allowing taxpayer-protected open space to be used as PennEast intends would be fiscally and environmentally irresponsible.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lance.house.gov/issues/penneast-pipeline-project|accessdate=Jan 2, 2017|title=PennEast Pipeline Project|website=house.gov|publisher=US House of Representatives}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/mercer/index.ssf/2016/01/federal_state_officials_call_for_halt_to_penneast.html|date=Jan 25, 2016|accessdate=Jan 2, 2017|title=Federal, state lawmakers call for halt to $1.2B PennEast pipeline proposal|website=nj.com|publisher=NJ Advance Media}}</ref> He has also said that the project would be harmful to farmland preservation along the [[Delaware River]] Watershed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hunterdon-county-democrat/index.ssf/2015/02/penneast_pipeline_opposed_by_almost_everybody_spea.html|title=PennEast pipeline opposed by almost everybody speaking at FERC meeting|website=Nj.com|publisher=Hunterdon Democrat|last1=Wright|first1=Terry|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, he said \"it is my hope that PennEast Pipeline company representatives will reexamine the project's proposed path and work with New Jersey's two U.S. Senators, the congressional delegation, state and local elected officials as well as concerned citizens in presenting a new plan that protects property rights and preserves public and private lands.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/local/hunterdon-county/2014/10/12/lance-opposes-pipeline-route-hunterdon/17058711/|date=Oct 12, 2014|title=Lance opposes pipeline route in Hunterdon|website=mycentraljersey.com|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=Jan 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2014, he voted in favor of H.R. 5078, the Waters of the United States Regulatory Overreach Protection Act of 2014. The purpose of the act was to prevent the Environmental Protection Agency and the Army Corps of Engineers from moving forward with a change to the [[Clean Water Rule]], which defines \"[[waters of the United States]]\" (the EPA is tasked with protecting the waters of the United States). Farmers feared that the rule would include their drainage ditches, while the EPA said that it would apply only to waters found in wetlands next to larger bodies that are 'waters of the United States'.\" H.R. 5078 passed but never took effect because the related Senate bill was never acted on. On January 13, 2016, he voted to invoke cloture on a joint resolution repealing the Clean Water Rule that defines \"waters of the United States\" which fall under the jurisdiction of the Corps of Engineers and the EPA. The resolution was vetoed by President Obama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015/05/27/epa-expands-clean-water-regulations|title=EPA Broadens Clean Water Regulations|author=Alan Neuheuser|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=Jan 6, 2018|publisher=US News & World Report|website=www.usnews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/5078|publisher=US House of Representatives|date=September 9, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2018|title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 489|website=congress.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2014/09/waters_of_the_united_states_epa_s_proposed_update_to_the_clean_water_act.html|date=September 11, 2014|accessdate=Jan 6, 2018|publisher=Slate|title=Trench Warfare|author=Boer Deng|website=www.slate.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2016/roll045.xml|publisher=US House of Representatives|date=January 13, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2018|title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 45|website=house.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2014/roll489.xml|title=H.R.5078 - Waters of the United States Regulatory Overreach Protection Act of 2014|publisher=US House of Representatives|date=Sep 9, 2014|accessdate=Jan 6, 2018|website=house.gov}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/opinion/index.ssf/2017/02/another_red-letter_week_for_new_jerseys_gop_delega.html|title=These N.J. congressmen voted to loosen gun laws, deceive workers {{!}} Editorial|work=NJ.com|access-date=April 1, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Todd Mitchell, Lance's chief of staff, characterized him as a skeptic on human involvement in climate change, saying that he believes that \"climate change is occurring and human activity is a contributing factor. But it's uncertain how much of the warming is attributable to humans and how much is attributable to other factors.\"<ref name=huffpo/> On December 1, 2015, he voted for S.J. Res. 24, to repeal the [[Clean Power Plan]] rules published by the EPA on October 23, 2015, that would have established the first national carbon dioxide emission guidelines for existing power plants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucsusa.org/our-work/global-warming/reduce-emissions/what-is-the-clean-power-plan#.WlC0UiOZNE4|title=The Clean Power Plan: A Climate Game Changer|publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists|website=ucs.org|accessdate=Jan 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrdc.org/sites/default/files/pollution-standards-epa-plan-summary.pdf|publisher=National Resources Defense Council|title=Carbon Pollution Standards for Existing Power Plants|accessdate=Jan 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.epa.gov/epa/cleanpowerplan/fact-sheet-clean-power-plan-overview.html|title=FACT SHEET: Clean Power Plan Overview|publisher=Environmental Protection Agency|accessdate=Jan 6, 2018}}</ref> At a town hall in April 2017, he embraced the need to address man-made climate change.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/04/14/523809375/man-in-the-middle-new-jerseys-leonard-lance-takes-heat-from-all-sides|website=NPR|title=Man In The Middle: New Jersey's Leonard Lance Takes Heat From All Sides|author=Susan Davis|date=April 14, 2017|access-date=Jan 6, 2018|publisher=National Public Radio}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after a group opposing his candidacy sent out a mailer criticizing Lance's environmental record, Jeff Tittel of the New Jersey [[Sierra Club]] defended Lance, saying he had \"an excellent record.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.app.com/capitolquickies/2008/10/23/environmentalists-defend-lance/|title=Environmentalists defend Lance|website=APP.com|publisher=Gannett|accessdate=Jan 2, 2017}}</ref> In 2009, Lance was one of only eight Republicans in the House who voted in favor of the [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]], a bill that included a [[Emissions trading|cap and trade]] provision to address global warming.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Friedman |first1=Matt |title=Conservatives angry at Lance, LoBiondo and Smith over cap-and-trade vote |url=http://observer.com/2009/06/conservatives-angry-at-lance-lobiondo-and-smith-over-cap-and-trade-vote/ |accessdate=19 July 2018 |publisher=Observer |date=June 29, 2009}}</ref><ref name=huffpo>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/roger-witherspoon/the-evolution-of-rep-leon_b_5698706.html|title=The Evolution of Rep. Leonard Lance: Environmentalist to Climate Change Denier|website=The Huffington Post|last1=Witherspoon|first1=Roger|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> However, Tittel has since soured on Lance, suggesting in a 2018 op-ed in the New Jersey Star-Ledger that Lance \"used to vote for the environment and now does not.\"<ref>Tittel, Jeff, [https://www.nj.com/opinion/index.ssf/2018/04/earth_day_2018.html Earth Day started as political movement to save the planet from men like Trump | Opinion] NJ.com, April 22, 2018 (retrieved 8/10/18)</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\nLance was one of nine lawmakers investigated by the [[United States House Committee on Ethics|House Ethics Committee]] for taking a trip in May 2013 to [[Turkey]] and [[Azerbaijan]] paid for by the Azerbaijan state-owned oil company;<ref name=twsNJcom433>Jonathan D. Salant, June 22, 2015, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/06/house_ethics_panel_extends_probe_of_previously_app.html House ethics panel continues probe of Lance trip], Retrieved January 26, 2017, \"...questions arose about whether the trips complied with the requirements for such travel....\"</ref> Lance was later cleared of wrongdoing by the committee.<ref name=twsNJcom49200>Jonathan D. Salant, August 1, 2015, NJ.com, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/08/nj_rep_lance_cleared_in_house_ethics_probe.html N.J. Rep. Lance cleared in House ethics probe], Retrieved January 26, 2017, \"...&nbsp;Because the House travelers acted in good faith, and the evidence was inconclusive as to the true source of funds for the travel, the committee concluded that the trips did not constitute an impermissible gift of travel,&nbsp;...\"</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Lance voted against the [[Iran Nuclear Deal]] in what he described as 'one of the most consequential votes' he has taken in Congress.<ref name=\"centraljersey.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.centraljersey.com/news/hillsborough_beacon/th-district-congressman-lance-votes-against-iran-nuclear-deal/article_3300453e-5af3-11e5-81e6-1342f19593c2.html|title=7TH DISTRICT: Congressman Lance votes against Iran nuclear deal|website=Centraljersey.com|publisher=centraljersey.com|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> He said that the agreement does not prevent the world\u2019s leading state sponsor of terrorism from attaining nuclear weapons.<ref name=\"centraljersey.com\" /> Since President Obama signed the Iran Nuclear Deal, Lance has sponsored legislation that would add additional sanctions on Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tapinto.net/towns/springfield/articles/lance-statement-on-iran-sanctions-2|title=Lance Statement on Iran Sanctions|website=TapintoSpringfield.com|publisher=Springfield Patch|last1=Dickson|first1=Ellen|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLance believes that Israel is entitled to its independence and that any Middle East peace pact must involve the recognition of Israel\u2019s right to exist as a free, Jewish State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc-news/watch/trump-issues-new-sanctions-against-iran-869425219732|title=Trump issues new sanctions against Iran|website=Msnbc.com|publisher=NBC}}</ref>\n\n=== Guns ===\nAccording to a 2016 analysis by political nonprofit [[Vote Smart]], Lance generally opposes gun control legislation.<ref name=twsVoteSmart787>VoteSmart, [https://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/4443/leonard-lance/#.Wl1IPyinHrc Leonard Lance's Issue Positions (Political Courage Test)], Retrieved January 15, 2017, \"...Guns: Do you generally support gun-control legislation? NO...\"</ref> In 2013, Lance was criticized by the father of a [[Virginia Tech shootings|Virginia Tech]] victim who wanted Lance to be more supportive of [[gun control]] measures.<ref name=twsHD101>NJ.com, January 2013, Suburban News, [http://www.nj.com/hunterdon-county-democrat/index.ssf/2013/01/raritan_township_father_of_son.html Father of school shooting victim demands action on guns from Rep. Lance], Retrieved January 15, 2017, \"...father whose son was killed in the shootings at Virginia Tech in 2007 directed some tough talk to lawmakers today, especially Congressman Leonard Lance...\"</ref> In 2016, Lance disagreed with members of Congress who staged a [[sit-in]] to force a vote on gun control.<ref name=twsPatch49494>Alexis Tarrazi, Patch, June 23, 2016, [https://patch.com/new-jersey/westfield/union-countys-rep-leonard-lance-speaks-out-against-gun-control-sit Union County's Rep. Leonard Lance Speaks Out Against Gun Control Sit-In], Retrieved January 15, 2017</ref> In March 2017, Lance was one of two House Republicans who broke with their party to oppose the Veterans 2nd Amendment Protection Act, which \"would require a judge to rule that veterans posed a danger to themselves or others before they could be denied the right to buy guns.\" The NRA had spoken out in support of the legislation.<ref name=twsNJcom909>Jonathan Salant, NJ.com, March 20, 2017, [http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/03/what_happened_after_the_nra_spent_23m_to_elect_a_r.html N.J. Republican says no to NRA bill allowing 'mentally incompetent' vets to buy guns], Retrieved January 15, 2017</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Lance opposed the Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act, which would require states to honor concealed weapons permits for people who got them in other states. Lance was one of 24 co-sponsors on legislation that would ban bump stocks.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan|title=Florida school shooting reignites gun control debate: How your lawmakers have voted under Trump|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/02/these_are_the_only_actions_congress_has_taken_on_g.html|accessdate=27 February 2018|publisher=NJ Advance Media|date=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Lance read a letter on the U.S. House floor urging Speaker of the House [[Paul Ryan]] to schedule a vote on legislation that would improve the national background check system for gun purchases. The letter, signed by 19 Republican members of the U.S. House, said passing the bill, which has been introduced by U.S. Senators [[John Cornyn]] (R) and [[Chris Murphy]] (D), would be an \"important step toward making our country safer from gun violence.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeBonis|first1=Mike|last2=Stein|first2=Jeff|title=House Republicans push Ryan to hold vote on background-check bill|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/house-republicans-push-ryan-to-hold-vote-on-background-check-bill/2018/02/23/3d3e3aa0-18de-11e8-b681-2d4d462a1921_story.html|accessdate=27 February 2018|publisher=Washington Post|date=February 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan|title=These House Republicans, including some from N.J., want improved gun background checks|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/02/these_nj_republicans_want_the_house_to_improve_gun.html|accessdate=27 February 2018|publisher=NJ Advance Media|date=February 24, 2018}}</ref> That same month, he called for a lifting of the 1996 federal ban of research into gun violence by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] and co-sponsored legislation which would lift the ban.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jackson|first1=Herb|title=Pascrell: Trump is a 'liar' on mental health checks for gun buyers|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2018/02/27/bill-pascrell-president-donald-trump-liar-mental-health-checks-gun-buyers/376825002/|accessdate=28 February 2018|publisher=NorthJersey|date=February 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Weixel|first1=Nathaniel|title=Florida shooting reopens CDC gun research debate|url=http://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/374308-florida-shooting-reopens-cdc-gun-research-debate|accessdate=28 February 2018|publisher=The Hill|date=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Health care ===\nLance has been a critic of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act (Obamacare)]] since its inception, voting against it in 2009 and voting to repeal it on multiple occasions. Lance voted to send the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]], the Republican Party's replacement plan for Obamacare, out of committee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/03/house_democrats_target_njs_lance_in_ad_campaign.html|title=Democrats target N.J.'s Lance over an Obamacare repeal vote|work=NJ.com|access-date=March 30, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> He ultimately opposed the legislation on the House floor, becoming the first House Republican in New Jersey to oppose the legislation, and one of 20 who voted against the final bill.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lanktree|first1=Graham|title=Why Did 20 Republicans Vote Against Donald Trump's American Health Care Act?|url=http://www.newsweek.com/why-did-20-republicans-vote-against-donald-trump-american-health-care-act-595111|accessdate=22 May 2018|publisher=Newsweek|date=May 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLance is the Republican chairman of the Rare Disease Caucus, a group whose goal is to get Members of Congress to support passing bills that help people who suffer from rare diseases.<ref name=\"Hunterdon County Democrat\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/hunterdon-county-democrat/index.ssf/2014/12/congressman_leonard_lance_will_1.html|title=Congressman Leonard Lance will continue as Republican Chair of Congressional Rare Disease Caucus|website=nj.com|publisher=Hunterdon County Democrat|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> As part of his work for the Rare Disease Caucus Lance in 2013 re-introduced the Modernizing Our Drug and Diagnostic Evaluation and Regulatory Network Cures (MODDERN) Act, a bipartisan bill intended to encourage new innovative treatments for a variety of diseases and ailments.<ref name=\"Hunterdon County Democrat\" /> The MODDERN Drug Act proposes to reevaluate and reintroduce drugs that were once in the development phase, back into production and testing. This bill would benefit patients suffering from a variety of ailments including but not limited to: degenerative conditions, cancer, and autoimmune diseases.<ref name=\"Hunterdon County Democrat\" />\n\nIn 2014, Lance introduced the Excellence in Mental Health Act, which was signed into law by President [[Barack Obama]] later that same year. The legislation expanded access to mental health services by providing additional federal funding for community mental health centers. In 2016, Lance sponsored the Expand Excellence in Mental Health Act, which would expand the legislation's mental health planning grants into an additional 24 states.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Deak|first1=Mike|title=Lance wants federal ban on gun violence research lifted|url=https://www.mycentraljersey.com/story/news/politics/2018/02/16/lance-wants-federal-ban-gun-violence-research-lifted/345342002/|accessdate=28 February 2018|publisher=MyCentralJersey.com|date=February 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Turpin|first1=Craig|title=Lance comes to N.J. to promote mental health care bill|url=http://www.nj.com/somerset/index.ssf/2016/04/lance_outlines_mental_health_care_path_at_carrier.html|accessdate=28 February 2018|publisher=NJ.com|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Immigration ===\nLance opposes amnesty and supports requiring employers to use the e-verify background check system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njspotlight.com/stories/16/06/06/district-7/|title=Lance, Seeking Fifth Term, Faces Two Challengers in Gop Primary in 7th |publisher=NJ Spotlight|last1=Jennings|first1=Rob|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Lance became the lead Republican sponsor of the Reunite Children with their Parents Act, which was introduced by Democrat [[Brendan Boyle]]. The legislation seeks to  \"force President Donald Trump's administration to reunify the families split apart under his immigration policy.\" It would  require the secretary of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] and the [[United States Attorney General]] to reunite asylum-seeking children who were taken from their parents when crossing the U.S. border.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salant |first1=Jonathan |title=This N.J. Republican seeks to force Trump to reunite immigrant families his policies separated |url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/06/this_nj_congressman_wants_to_force_trump_to_reunit.html |accessdate=15 July 2018 |publisher=NJ.com |date=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Internet regulation===\nLance was one of the 107 members of Congress who signed a letter of support towards the [[Federal Communications Commission]]'s (FCC) efforts to repeal [[net neutrality]]. Lance has received $290,550 in campaign contributions from ISP companies since 1989.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rogers|first1=Kaleigh|last2=Koebler|first2=Jason|title=Here's a List of the Members of Congress Who Just Told Ajit Pai to Repeal Net Neutrality|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/7xwknx/republican-members-of-congress-fcc-letter|accessdate=15 January 2018|publisher=Motherboard}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Lance voted to reverse an FCC privacy rule that prevented internet service providers from selling their customers' browsing data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/29/15100620/congress-fcc-isp-web-browsing-privacy-fire-sale|title=The 265 members of Congress who sold you out to ISPs, and how much it cost to buy them|date=March 29, 2017|website=The Verge|access-date=April 1, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Explaining his vote, Lance said that the regulation created a \"false sense of privacy\" by treating internet service providers differently.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/3185880/privacy/us-house-votes-to-undo-broadband-privacy-rules.html|title=Congress dismantles Internet privacy rules, allowing ISPs to sell your web history|work=PCWorld|access-date=April 1, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2017-03-28/house-votes-to-let-internet-providers-sell-user-browsing-data-without-consent|title=house-votes-to-let-internet-providers-sell-user-browsing-data-without-consent|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402100113/https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2017-03-28/house-votes-to-let-internet-providers-sell-user-browsing-data-without-consent|archive-date=2017-04-02|dead-url=yes|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nLance has a 48 out of 100 rating from the [[Human Rights Commission]] regarding his voting record on [[LGBT rights]].<ref name=\"HRCScore\">{{cite book|title=Congressional Scorecard|date=2016|publisher=Human Rights Coalition|location=Washington, D.C.|page=18|url=https://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/114thCongressionalScorecard.pdf|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> Lance opposes same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/4443/leonard-lance/ |title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref> Lance voted against repeal of [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Represent |url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/votes/111/house/2/638 |title=House Vote 638 - Repeals 'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' &#124; Represent &#124; ProPublica |publisher=Projects.propublica.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he co-sponsored Barney Frank\u2019s [[Employment Non-Discrimination Act]], a bill that would have prohibited employment discrimination on the basis of actual or perceived sexual orientation or gender identity by employers, employment agencies, labor organizations, or joint labor-management committees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/111th-congress/house-bill/3017|title=H.R.3017 - Employment Non-Discrimination Act of 2009|website=Congress.gov|publisher=Congress.gov}}</ref>  He was also one of only 18 Republicans to vote for the [[Hate Crimes Prevention Act]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/111th-congress/house-bill/1913/actions|title=H.R.1913 - Local Law Enforcement Hate Crimes Prevention Act of 2009|website=Congress.gov|publisher=Congress.gov|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Marijuana===\n\nLance has a \"D\" rating from [[NORML]] regarding his voting record on [[cannabis]]-related matters.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=New Jersey Scorecard - NORML.org - Working to Reform Marijuana Laws|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/new-jersey|website=norml.org|accessdate=December 21, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLance married his wife, Heidi A. Rohrbach, who is a VP at [[JPMorgan Chase]], in August 1996. They have a son, named Peter Frank.<ref>{{ Citation\n | title= Heidi Rohrbach, Leonard Lance\n | publisher=NY Times\n | date=August 11, 1996\n | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/11/style/heidi-rohrbach-leonard-lance.html\n | accessdate = July 17, 2011\n }}</ref> He is a former trustee of the [[Newark Museum]], of [[Centenary College of New Jersey|Centenary College]] in [[Hackettstown, New Jersey|Hackettstown]] and of [[McCarter Theatre]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lance.house.gov/ Congressman Leonard Lance] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.leonardlance.com/ Leonard Lance for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_Jersey/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Leonard_Lance_%5BR-07%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|leonardlance}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSucce